3. How to compute the damage realised by a Pokmon?
The damage a Pokmon will do to its opponent is given by:
Damage formula = o or
1

Power
ATT

+ 1
To illustrate this formula we consider an Exeggutor (A) perfect at level 30 launching Solar Beam to a Kyogre at level 40.
oor () + 1 guarantees that the minimum damage of any attack is 1.
Power is the power of the considered move, for Solar Beam, it is 180.
ATT is the givers attack statistic. For instance, for Exeggutor (A) at level 30 with 15 as IV_ATT, it would be (230+15)0.7317 = 179.
OPP_DEF is the opponents defense statistic. For instance, for Kyogre at level 40 with 15 as IV_DEF, it would be (228+15)0.7903 = 192.
Multipliers could be STAB, WAB, FAB and Eectiveness.
STAB is an acronym for Same Type Attack Bonus. If a Pokemon uses a move that matches one of its types, then the attack damage gets a 1.2 multiplier.
WAB is an acronym for Weather Attack Bonus. If a Pokemon uses a move that matches one of the boosted types in the current weather, then the attack gets a 1.2
multiplier, same as that of STAB.
FAB is an acronym for Friendship Attack Bonus. Friend bonuses are 3%, 5%, 7% or 10% depending on your level of friendship.
Eectiveness refers to the multiplier applied to using a "super eective" or "not very eective" move.
Not very eective (at all!) 0.39

(Super!) super eective 2.56

4. Which moves to choose for a Pokemon?
Each Pokemon has a fast move and a charged move. Both together dene the damages the Pokmon will realise.
Each move is dened by the damage it realises, its duration and the energy it generates (for fast moves) or uses (for charged moves).
Charged move energies are dened by the number of bars:
energy of 33.33 energy of 50 energy of 100
The goal is then to choose the best moves that realise the most damages per second. We consider the example of Metagross: is Meteor Mash or Flash Cannon more
interesting? From https://pokemon.gameinfo.io, we get the following table:
Meteor Mash Flash Cannon
Base damage 100 100
Move duration 2600 ms 2700 ms
Damage window 2300 - 2500 ms 1600 - 2500 ms
Energy -50 -100
DPS 38.5 37
EPS -19.2 -37
DPS is the damage per second for this move (= Base damage/Move duration), whereas EPS is the energy used per second (= Base damage/Energy).
Both attacks realise 100 as base damage, and have similar Move duration. However Meteor Mash needs less energy than Flash Cannon; a player will launch two Meteor
Mash for one Flash Cannon, and realise twice more damage in the same time. This is reected in the EPS.
Therefore, Meteor Mash is much more interesting than Flash Cannon.
We usually compute the global and neutral DPS for each couple (fast, charge) to see the number of damage per second the Pokmon realises by combining its fast and
charged moves. Computation is complex, as it needs to consider also the damage realised by the opponent which brings energy to the giver. The DPS must also consider
"Same Type Attack Bonus" (STAB, 25% damage boost of a move when it is the same type as one of the types of the Pokmon using the move). Read
https://pokemongo.gamepress.gg/tdo-how-calculate-pokemon-ability-outdated for more details.
However, such table containing all neutral DPS is available at https://pokemongo.gamepress.gg/comprehensive-dps-spreadsheet. For Metagross, they write:
Pokemon Fast Move Charged Move DPS TDO DPS

DPS of (Bullet Punch, Meteor Mash) is much higher than DPS of (Bullet Punch, Flash Cannon).

5. Which Pokemon to choose for levelling up?
They must be chosen based on their:
Damage Per Second (DPS) dened by their fast and charged move: it represents how much damage a Pokmon can make in a second.
Eective Health (EH) is computed via the formula (at level 40):
EH = (base DEF + DEF_IV) (base HP + HP_IV)

900
Total Damage Output (TDO) represents how much damage a Pokmon can make before it faints. It is computed via TDO = DPS EH

6. How dicult are Raid bosses?
Raid boss have the attack and defend statistics of a perfect level 40 Pokmon, but their HP depends on the diculty of the raid:

Damages realised by the raid boss are identical to a Pokmon level 40 with ATT_IV = 15.
For a 5-head boss, you must realise 15000/300 = 50 HP per second; same damage to realise per second for a 4-head boss. The main diculty of a 5-head boss is that it
has more HP, and therefore you will need more time, more Pokmon and more revives.
Diculty of a raid boss will mainly depends on the boss defence statistic (the higher is defense is, the more time you will need to defeat it).
You need to play on resistance of your Pokmon, if you want to use less potion to defeat it
You need to play on the boss vulnerability, if you want to defeat it faster.

7. How are IV important?
If the Pokmon has an important base attack statistic, there will be no dierence between ATT_IV = 14 and ATT_IV = 15.
It is recommended to that a high ATT_IV for Pokmon with low DPS.
Regarding to bulkiness (DEF_IV and HP_IV), the defence statistic inuences how fast your Pokmon will die, whereas the HP statistic tells you the total number of HP
your Pokmon will have. Usually, it is more interesting to have a higher DEF_IV than HP_IV.
It is recommended to that a high DEF_IV and HP_IV for Pokmon with low Eective Health.
It is also recommended to level up at least to level 30 your Pokmon. At level 30, your Pokemon is already at 92.6% of its capacity!

The more you want to level up your Pokmon, the more expansive it will be. Level 35 is ne (where your Pokmon is at 96.4% of its capacity), but level 30 is good too (92.6% of
its capacity). There is an ideal level depending on each Pokmon and its opponent:
above a certain level, it will not be more resistant (its oponent will be able to inige a certain number of fast and charged attacks until your Pokmon dies). It is called the
bulkpoint.
above a certain level (usually dierent from the bulkpoint), your Pokmon fast attack will do exactly the same damage (its due to the oor in the damage formula). It is
called the breakpoint.
For levelling up a Pokmon after level 35, if base stat 125, the dierence between an IV 15 and an IV 14 is one level. If base stat 265, the dierence between an IV 15 and
an IV 14 is one half-level.
